THE main object ol this book is to treat Caesar as an historiari. The text is that which 1 found prescribed by the University. I know that I am expressing the sentiments oi the Delegates os the Clarendon Press in thanking Professor Emanuel Hoffmann, of Vienna, ior the ready courtesy with which he responded to their nequest that I might be allowed to avail myseli ol his labours The previous editions oi which most use has been made are those oi Long, Moberly, Kraner, Dinter‚ and the American work by Allen and Greenough‚ with notes on the Roman military art by H. P. Judson. The neat little work by the last-named writer, on the Roman army in Caesar’s time, has also been consulted.

The source, however, to which 1 am conscious os the largest debt is Desjardins’ Geographie de la Gaule Romaine, a work oi exhaustive learning and sound judgement.
